>
  <p>
    Every time water leaves the house, solids settle to the bottom of the septic tank and slowly
    build into a sludge layer, while lighter material forms a scum layer on top. Pumping removes
    those layers before they build far enough to carry over into the drain field — which is the
    outcome worth avoiding, because drain-field trouble sits at the expensive end of septic
    problems. So the real question behind “how often” is “how fast does my tank fill,” and that
    varies from property to property.
  </p>

