  <h2>The Factors That Set Your Pumping Interval</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Tank size relative to the household.</strong> A smaller tank serving a full house
      fills faster than a larger tank serving the same number of people.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Number of people using the system.</strong> Every person adds daily load. Larger
      and multi-generation households — and rentals — reach service intervals sooner.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Water habits.</strong> Steady, spread-out water use is gentle on a system; heavy
      spikes (several loads of laundry in a day, long guest weekends) push more through at once.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Garbage-disposal use.</strong> Disposals send extra solids into the tank and can
      meaningfully speed up how fast the sludge layer builds.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>System condition and age.</strong> Failing baffles, past neglect or an aging system
      can shorten the practical interval between services.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why the Best Interval Comes From Your Last Service</h2>
  <p>
    Charts and rules of thumb can only generalize. The most useful number for your property comes
    from the tank itself: when a provider pumps or inspects it, they can see how full it actually
    was and tell you how much runway you had. That single observation turns “how often should I
    pump” from a guess into a plan tailored to how your household actually uses the system.
  </p>

