  <h2>Signs You May Be Due Sooner Than Expected</h2>
  <p>
    Between services, the system will usually tell you if it is filling faster than planned. Slow
    drains throughout the house, gurgling after water use, odors indoors or over the tank, or wet
    and unusually green areas over the drain field are all worth acting on rather than waiting for
    the calendar. Our guide to
    <a href="/resources/septic-problems/">septic problems and warning signs</a> covers what these
    symptoms can mean.
  </p>

  <h2>Setting Your Own Schedule</h2>
  <p>
    A workable approach is simple: have the tank serviced, ask the provider how full it was and
    what that suggests for your household, and use that to set your next interval — then adjust as
    your water use or household changes. Keeping a short record of service dates and what the
    provider observed makes every future decision easier. When it’s time, or if you’re simply not
    sure when the tank was last done, <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a> and a
    local provider can check the levels and advise.
  </p>

